I get to work with amazing
people, many of them

00:44:41.690 --> 00:44:43.944
women leaders, and their
teams who are really

00:44:43.944 --> 00:44:46.360
making that journey and helping
them to think through what

00:44:46.360 --> 00:44:48.480
are all the strategies
they can use, how can they

00:44:48.480 --> 00:44:50.756
be more effective and
be more efficient at it.

00:44:50.756 --> 00:44:52.630
And if you send me a
note to denise@thoughtle

00:44:52.630 --> 00:44:55.220
adershiplab.com--
denise@thoughtle

00:44:55.220 --> 00:44:59.510
adershiplab.com-- I will send
you a secret page on my website

00:44:59.510 --> 00:45:01.470
which has a whole set
of worksheets which

00:45:01.470 --> 00:45:04.790
go with the book, because I
really believe that there is

00:45:04.790 --> 00:45:06.910
some very basic steps
that you can take,

00:45:06.910 --> 00:45:09.290
but sometimes taking them
from just reading a book

00:45:09.290 --> 00:45:10.530
can feel overwhelming.

00:45:10.530 --> 00:45:12.920
The book is written as
a seven-step process,

00:45:12.920 --> 00:45:15.610
with a ton of resources and
questions to ask yourself,

00:45:15.610 --> 00:45:18.310
but the worksheets are
sort of an adjunct to that.

00:45:18.310 --> 00:45:20.319
All right, so, happy to
take a few questions.

00:45:20.319 --> 00:45:21.860
I know we're running
up against time,

00:45:21.860 --> 00:45:24.550
but who has a question for me?

00:45:24.550 --> 00:45:25.500
How long does it take.

00:45:25.500 --> 00:45:27.910
AUDIENCE: Yeah, how long it
takes to from [INAUDIBLE]--

00:45:27.910 --> 00:45:29.868
DENISE BROSSEAU: From
leader to thought leader.

00:45:29.868 --> 00:45:32.333
Yeah, I wish I could
say, oh, about a week.

00:45:32.333 --> 00:45:34.140
All done.

00:45:34.140 --> 00:45:36.800
Honestly, everybody takes
a little different path,

00:45:36.800 --> 00:45:39.520
and everybody takes a
little different timeline.

00:45:39.520 --> 00:45:43.820
For me, it was really
in a year because it was

00:45:43.820 --> 00:45:45.070
kind of I was the go-to girl.

00:45:45.070 --> 00:45:47.320
I was one of three or four
people in the United States

00:45:47.320 --> 00:45:49.819
who knew anything about a topic
in the middle of the dot.com

00:45:49.819 --> 00:45:52.060
craze, and it was the
hot topic and everybody

00:45:52.060 --> 00:45:53.165
wanted someone to talk to.

00:45:53.165 --> 00:45:55.540
We had an organization, we
were doing interesting things,

00:45:55.540 --> 00:45:57.460
we were out showcasing
women entrepreneurs.

00:45:57.460 --> 00:46:00.850
And so that's why I got this
opportunity and really kind of,

00:46:00.850 --> 00:46:02.730
over the next year
after the conference,

00:46:02.730 --> 00:46:05.160
just kind of went everywhere.

00:46:05.160 --> 00:46:08.054
Others of my clients have taken
definitely longer than that.

00:46:08.054 --> 00:46:10.220
You know, for Von, it was
three years from beginning

00:46:10.220 --> 00:46:12.940
to getting her head hunted to
the job at the chancellor's

00:46:12.940 --> 00:46:13.560
office.

00:46:13.560 --> 00:46:17.850
From absolute zero-- a brand-new
job, no team, no resources,

00:46:17.850 --> 00:46:20.580
nothing-- to being head-hunted.

00:46:20.580 --> 00:46:21.660
That was three years.

00:46:21.660 --> 00:46:23.390
So everybody's different.

00:46:23.390 --> 00:46:25.360
And by the way, it
doesn't really-- to me,

00:46:25.360 --> 00:46:28.430
it's not so much about the time
it takes, but the impact you

00:46:28.430 --> 00:46:29.989
have along the way.

00:46:29.989 --> 00:46:31.530
So much of this is
about figuring out

00:46:31.530 --> 00:46:33.530
how am I going to
measure my success.

00:46:33.530 --> 00:46:35.620
Am I measuring it
by my followership?

00:46:35.620 --> 00:46:38.510
Am I measuring it by
people adopting my ideas?

00:46:38.510 --> 00:46:39.980
Am I measuring it
by just feeling

00:46:39.980 --> 00:46:41.930
more career satisfaction,
which you mentioned.

00:46:41.930 --> 00:46:44.650
Do I just feel more like
I'm leaving that legacy

00:46:44.650 --> 00:46:47.250
that I want to leave.

00:46:47.250 --> 00:46:49.470
That kind of measurement
stick is a little

00:46:49.470 --> 00:46:51.900
different than just a timeline.

00:46:51.900 --> 00:46:55.134
AUDIENCE: I imagine to be
a really good and diligent

00:46:55.134 --> 00:46:56.550
thought leader
that you have to be

00:46:56.550 --> 00:46:58.840
able to take a lot of bumps
and bruises along the way,

00:46:58.840 --> 00:47:01.630
and a lot of resilience and
have a lot of perseverance.

00:47:01.630 --> 00:47:06.150
So I'm just interested
to hear-- that, to me, I

00:47:06.150 --> 00:47:08.017
feel like is sometimes
where I hesitate,

00:47:08.017 --> 00:47:10.350
like do I want to take all
the bumps and bruises coming.

00:47:10.350 --> 00:47:11.530
DENISE BROSSEAU: Absolutely.

00:47:11.530 --> 00:47:13.654
AUDIENCE: So I'm curious
to know your approach when

00:47:13.654 --> 00:47:14.627
those come on the road.

00:47:14.627 --> 00:47:16.210
DENISE BROSSEAU:
Yeah, there's arrows.

00:47:16.210 --> 00:47:18.390
There are definitely
arrows that come our way.

00:47:18.390 --> 00:47:20.770
But here's the thing that's
so fascinating to me.

00:47:20.770 --> 00:47:23.689
Usually, in our mind, they're
way bigger than the actuality.

00:47:23.689 --> 00:47:26.230
All the different people that
I've worked with over the eight

00:47:26.230 --> 00:47:28.563
years I've been doing this
work, there have been arrows,

00:47:28.563 --> 00:47:29.630
I'm not going to kid you.

00:47:29.630 --> 00:47:31.990
But usually, we imagine
them to be way bigger,

00:47:31.990 --> 00:47:35.150
and we stop ourselves because
we think that's going to happen.

00:47:35.150 --> 00:47:36.900
And yet, what we
find is, when we

00:47:36.900 --> 00:47:38.550
do we hit a bump
in the road-- I'm

00:47:38.550 --> 00:47:40.600
not saying we don't have
them, I have one client

00:47:40.600 --> 00:47:44.910
who put out a post that really
wasn't well-researched and got

00:47:44.910 --> 00:47:48.460
some real pushback on you don't
have the facts-- but being

00:47:48.460 --> 00:47:51.670
able to clarify and build--
re-build the credentials

00:47:51.670 --> 00:47:55.460
after that and the credibility
after that by owning it up.

00:47:55.460 --> 00:47:57.340
The truth is like anything.

00:47:57.340 --> 00:47:59.280
Innovation is about
making mistakes.

00:47:59.280 --> 00:48:01.130
Innovation is about
bumps in the road

00:48:01.130 --> 00:48:03.070
and overcoming those bumps.

00:48:03.070 --> 00:48:06.410
And by having a community or
having someone else next to you

00:48:06.410 --> 00:48:08.920
to lean on, I highly
recommend that.

00:48:08.920 --> 00:48:10.470
You know, that definitely helps.

00:48:10.470 --> 00:48:12.400
And then lastly, I
would say that there's

00:48:12.400 --> 00:48:15.220
this great quote by a guy
named Hank Lieber that I put

00:48:15.220 --> 00:48:17.550
in the book, and he
talks about there really

00:48:17.550 --> 00:48:19.470
is no such thing as failure.

00:48:19.470 --> 00:48:22.400
He says, failure is if you keep
doing the same mistake over

00:48:22.400 --> 00:48:23.970
and over and over.

00:48:23.970 --> 00:48:26.360
Otherwise, it's just learning.

00:48:26.360 --> 00:48:29.220
And we all want to keep
learning, so keep going.

00:48:29.220 --> 00:48:32.610
Which I think is just a very
powerful reframe of this.

00:48:32.610 --> 00:48:34.770
Yes, people are
going to bump into me

00:48:34.770 --> 00:48:37.190
and they're going to
question me and doubt me.

00:48:37.190 --> 00:48:40.350
But the more I can keep
going and learning from that,

00:48:40.350 --> 00:48:41.426
the stronger I get.

00:48:41.426 --> 00:48:43.550
As one of the women I
interviewed in the book said,

00:48:43.550 --> 00:48:46.789
you have to get ready for
when you're not ready.

00:48:46.789 --> 00:48:48.080
Because we're not ready, right?

00:48:48.080 --> 00:48:50.500
We weren't ready for the job
we have right now, were you?

00:48:50.500 --> 00:48:51.150
Right?

00:48:51.150 --> 00:48:52.150
We're not.

00:48:52.150 --> 00:48:54.990
But picking ourselves up,
brushing ourselves off,

00:48:54.990 --> 00:48:56.164
and keep going.

00:48:56.164 --> 00:48:58.080
But thank you all for
being here and thank you

00:48:58.080 --> 00:48:59.790
for playing with me today.

00:48:59.790 --> 00:49:00.632
[APPLAUSE]

00:49:00.632 --> 00:49:01.590
I really appreciate it.

00:49:01.590 --> 00:49:03.139
[APPLAUSE]

